  "text": "Stack protection mechanisms in LLVM/llvm-project are spread across several files:\n\n1. **StackProtector pass** (`llvm/lib/CodeGen/StackProtector.cpp`): This is the primary LLVM CodeGen pass (`class StackProtector : public FunctionPass`) that inserts stack canary (cookie) checks into functions. It is registered as 'Insert stack protectors' and analyses whether functions need protection (via `SSPLayoutAnalysis::requiresStackProtector`). The corresponding header declaring the pass interface is at `llvm/include/llvm/CodeGen/StackProtector.h`.\n\n2. **SafeStack pass** (`llvm/lib/CodeGen/SafeStack.cpp`): Implements the SafeStack mitigation (`class SafeStack` and `class SafeStackLegacyPass`), which separates stack allocations into a safe stack (for variables whose addresses are not taken or don't escape) and an unsafe stack (for potentially dangerous allocations). The layout helper is in `llvm/lib/CodeGen/SafeStackLayout.cpp`.\n\n3. **Header interface** (`llvm/include/llvm/CodeGen/StackProtector.h`): Declares the `StackProtector` FunctionPass class that the rest of the compiler includes when needing stack protection analysis.\n\n4. **Runtime `__stack_chk_fail`** (`libc/src/compiler/generic/__stack_chk_fail.cpp`): LLVM libc's implementation of the `__stack_chk_fail()` runtime function called when the stack canary check fails (detects a buffer overflow/stack smash). Note: this is under `libc/` rather than `compiler-rt/lib/builtins/`; the compiler-rt builtins directory does not contain a standalone `__stack_chk_fail` — it is typically provided by the OS libc or LLVM's own libc.\n\n5. **AddressSanitizer** (`llvm/lib/Transforms/Instrumentation/AddressSanitizer.cpp`): In `llvm/lib/Transforms/Instrumentation/`, the `FunctionStackPoisoner` class implements memory safety instrumentation for stack frames — it poisons/unpoisons stack memory around local variables to detect out-of-bounds accesses at runtime, directly related to stack frame protection."
}

