  "text": "Stack protection mechanisms in llvm/llvm-project are spread across several files:\n\n1. **StackProtector pass** (`llvm/lib/CodeGen/StackProtector.cpp`): The primary LLVM CodeGen pass (`class StackProtector : public FunctionPass`) that inserts stack canary (cookie) checks into functions. Registered as 'Insert stack protectors', it analyses via `SSPLayoutAnalysis::requiresStackProtector` whether functions need protection based on SSP attributes (-fstack-protector, -fstack-protector-strong, -fstack-protector-all).\n\n2. **SafeStack pass** (`llvm/lib/CodeGen/SafeStack.cpp`): Implements the SafeStack mitigation (`class SafeStack` and `class SafeStackLegacyPass`), which separates stack allocations into a safe stack (variables whose address does not escape) and an unsafe stack (potentially dangerous allocations). The unsafe stack is separately allocated to isolate it from the safe stack, preventing linear overflows from corrupting control data.\n\n3. **StackProtector header** (`llvm/include/llvm/CodeGen/StackProtector.h`): Declares the `StackProtector` FunctionPass interface used throughout the compiler backend.\n\n4. **Runtime `__stack_chk_fail`** (`libc/src/compiler/generic/__stack_chk_fail.cpp`): LLVM libc's implementation of the `__stack_chk_fail()` runtime function called when a stack canary mismatch is detected. Note: this lives under `libc/` rather than `compiler-rt/lib/builtins/`; the compiler-rt builtins directory does not include a standalone `__stack_chk_fail` — it is typically provided by the OS/system libc or LLVM's own libc.\n\n5. **AddressSanitizer** (`llvm/lib/Transforms/Instrumentation/AddressSanitizer.cpp`): Under `llvm/lib/Transforms/Instrumentation/`, the `FunctionStackPoisoner` class instruments stack frames for memory safety — it poisons and unpoisons redzones around local stack variables to detect out-of-bounds stack accesses at runtime, providing stack frame protection against buffer overflows."
}

